1317","Hodnet, Shropshire, England":"Hodnet, Shropshire, England","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Lawley, Shropshire, England":"Lawley, Shropshire, England","Stokesay, Shropshire, England":"Stokesay, Shropshire, England"},"en":{"1255–12 Jul 1347 ":"1255–12 July 1347","1255–1347":"1255–1347","1250–1316":"1250–1316","1290–1353":"1290–1353","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1292–1378":"1292–1378","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","about 1292":"about 1292","about 1290":"about 1290","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","12 Jul 1347 ":"12 July 1347","1292":"1292","unknown":"before 1290","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","1235":"1235","1378":"1378","11 Nov 1316":"11 November 1316","1255":"1255","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Hodnet, Shropshire, England":"Hodnet, Shropshire, England","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Lawley, Shropshire, England":"Lawley, Shropshire, England","Stokesay, Shropshire, England":"Stokesay, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hodnet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire): habitational name from Hodnet (Shropshire). The placename probably means ‘pleasant valley’, from Proto-Welsh <i>hǭd</i> + <i>nant</i>. This English name has been established in Ireland (Cork) since the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hoddinott","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodnett  ."]},{"name":"Hadnott","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodnett  ."]},{"name":"Hadnot","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodnett  ."]},{"name":"Hudnut","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Hudnott</b>, itself a variant of   Hodnett  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":35,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":60,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":73,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":82,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLe